      "sfies\nGauss's law for the vacuum, then it must be the constant electric field.\n\n-/\n\nnamespace Electromagnetism\nopen Distribution SchwartzMap\n\nnamespace OneDimVacuum\nopen Space StaticElectricField MeasureTheory\nnoncomputable section\n\n/-- The zero charge distribution in 1d space. -/\ndef chargeDistribution : ChargeDistribution 1 := 0\n\n/-- An electric field obey's Gauss's law for the vacuum in 1 dimension if and only if\n  it is the constant electric field. -/\n@[sorryful]\nlemma gaussLaw_iff (q ε : ℝ) (E : StaticElectricField 1) :\n    E.GaussLaw ε (chargeDistribution) ↔ ∃ m, E = constD 1 m := by\n  sorry\n```\n\nNow, we need to complete the proof. The goal is to show that if an electric field satisfies Gauss's law with the zero charge distribution, then it must be a constant field.\n\nLet's look at what `E.GaussLaw ε (chargeDistribution)` means. The definition of Gauss's law in the context is likely that the integral of the divergence of the electric field is equal to the charge distribution.\n\nBut in 1D, with the zero charge distribution, the integral of the divergence must be zero. But in 1D, the divergence of the electric field is just the derivative of the electric field with respect to position.\n\nWait, in 1D, the divergence of a vector field E is just the derivative of E with respect to x. So, Gauss's law would state that the integral of the derivative of E from some point a to point b is equal to the charge enclosed.\n\nBut in our case, the charge distribution is zero, so the integral of the derivative of E must be zero.\n\nBut the integral of the derivative of E from a to b is just E(b) - E(a). So, if this is zero for any interval [a, b], then E(b) = E(a) for all b, a. Therefore, E must be constant.\n\nSo in the proof, we need to show that if the integral of the derivative of E over any interval is zero, then E is constant.\n\nNow, let's try to complete the proof.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Nor