      "the divergence of a vector field `E` is just the derivative of the component of `E` with respect to the 1D coordinate. So if `E` is represented as a function `E(x)` where `x` is the 1D coordinate, then the divergence is `dE/dx`. Gauss's law then states `dE/dx = 0`.\n\nIf `dE/dx = 0`, then `E` must be a constant function. So there exists a constant `m` such that `E(x) = m` for all `x`. In the context of `StaticElectricField 1`, this would mean `E` is equal to the constant distribution `constD 1 m`.\n\nSo the proof should proceed as follows:\n\n1. Expand the definition of `E.GaussLaw ε chargeDistribution`. Since the charge distribution is zero, this will mean the divergence of `E` is zero.\n2. In 1D, the divergence is the derivative. So `dE/dx = 0`.\n3. If the derivative is zero, `E` is constant. So there exists `m` such that `E = constD 1 m`.\n4. This proves the forward direction. The reverse direction (if `E` is constant, then the divergence is zero) should be straightforward.\n\nLet's write out the formal proof in Lean 4.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.Real\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.Cauchy\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.Tax\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.Metric\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.InnerProduct\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.Normed\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.Real\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.Cauchy\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.Tax\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.Metric\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.InnerProduct\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.Normed\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Normed.Real\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Speci